 far away as India and the United States, the book challenges presumptions that Africa's global relationships have always been dictated by outsiders. Full of rich and often-surprising vignettes that outline forgotten trajectories of global trade and consumption, it powerfully demonstrates how contemporary globalization is foreshadowed in deep histories of intersecting and reciprocal relationships across vast distances.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aConsumer behaviorzAfrica, Eastern. 0aGlobalizationzAfrica, Eastern. 7aHISTORY / World.2bisacsh  a19th century.  aafrica.  aafrican consumers.  acareer.  acollege students.  aconsumer demands.  aconsumerism.  aconsumption.  aeast africa.  aeconomic change.  aengaging.  aglobal politics.  aglobal relationships.  aglobalization.  ahistorical.  aindia.  ainterconnectivity.  amaterialism.  amodern history.  anonfiction.  apolitical science.  apolitics.  apostcolonialism.  asocial change.  aunited states.  awestern expansion.  awestern interests.  awestern world.  aworld history.  aworld trade.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052025423740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094147240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520941472423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520941472/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY